feat(events): phase C v1 - backdated commits grouped by stand_datum

Add events/detect.py, events/commit.py and events/schema.py:

- detect_event_groups reads git status of the data repo, groups
  modified laws by their meta.json stand_datum and falls back to
  today when that is missing.
- commit_event_groups writes events/<year>/<event_id>.json per group
  and creates one git commit per group with GIT_AUTHOR_DATE and
  GIT_COMMITTER_DATE set to <stand_datum>T00:00:00Z.
- Remaining non-law changes (typically sources/current/gii-index.json)
  are gathered in one bookkeeping commit with today as date.

Add two CLI subcommands:

- commit-events: runs detect + commit on current working tree.
- sync: convenience wrapper running snapshot and commit-events back to
  back. This is the daily-driver used by the updated GitHub workflow.

v1 approximates the effective_date with stand_datum from GII; Phase C
v2 will plug in recht.bund.de for real per-paragraph events without
changing the surrounding schema.
